source: ## FAILFAST will abort when it runs into an issue

# load data into a dataframe from csv
ud1 = spark.read.load('/musicdata/UserDetailsWithIssues.csv', format='csv', header=True,mode='FAILFAST')

ud1.printSchema()
ud1.show()

# load data into a dataframe from csv
ud1 = spark.read.load('/musicdata/UserDetailsWithIssues.csv', format='csv', header=True,mode='FAILFAST')

ud1.count()
## We can force a full scan of the file with parsing, big files will take longer

# load data into a dataframe from csv
ud1 = spark.read.load('/musicdata/UserDetailsWithIssues.csv', format='csv', header=True, badRecordsPath='/spark/errors/',mode='FAILFAST')
# Databricks has an option called badrecordspath that is not available in open source Spark
ud1.collect()
## We can let Spark drop all the bad records and keep going but we will never know what the issue was!

# load data into a dataframe from csv
ud1 = spark.read.load('/musicdata/UserDetailsWithIssues.csv', format='csv', header=True,mode='DROPMALFORMED')

len(ud1.collect())
## We can specify a special column to trap the problem

#specify the schema
from pyspark.sql.types import *

customSchema = StructType([
    StructField("UserID", StringType(), True),        
    StructField("Gender", StringType(), True),
    StructField("Age", IntegerType(), True),
    StructField("Country", StringType(), True),
    StructField("SignupString", StringType(), True),
    StructField("_corrupt_record", StringType(), True) 
])

ud2 = spark.read.load('/musicdata/UserDetailsWithIssues.csv', format="csv", header="true", sep=',', schema=customSchema,mode='PERMISSIVE') #permissive is the default
## And write down the problem records
## At this point the bad records are still inside the original file and the dataframe
